WEBVTT

00:03.727 --> 00:12.301
Has there been, over the years, a substantial 
increase in students in the field of poultry

00:03.727 --> 00:12.301
husbandry? And has there been a change in the 
background of the students? By background, I

00:17.269 --> 00:22.859
would have to say, let me preface that by saying a 
geographical background. Have they come from

00:22.879 --> 00:25.583
different areas of the world? Well, of course, I 
inherited, when I took over the department, I

00:26.120 --> 00:38.072
inherited no records.

00:38.092 --> 00:47.401
And so it's not going to be easy for me to answer that 
accurately. But in terms of numbers of students,

00:52.546 --> 01:09.206
there has distinctly been an increase in numbers 
of students, both undergraduate, but

00:52.546 --> 01:09.206
particularly at the graduate level.

01:09.467 --> 01:21.321
We have, since

01:09.467 --> 01:21.321
about 1950,

01:09.467 --> 01:21.321
we have probably had more graduate students in the 
poetry department at Texas A&M University than

01:22.246 --> 01:28.675
any other institution in the United States. I 
don't think there's any challenge, even a

01:29.116 --> 01:33.021
beginning challenge there. And so that the 
increase in students has majorly been at the

01:34.704 --> 01:48.203
graduate level.

01:48.436 --> 01:53.005
Has this increase been primarily students from 
the United States or from abroad? They've been

01:53.225 --> 01:54.648
both, both. Yes, indeed, they've been both. Now 
the undergraduate students, there's just been a

01:58.275 --> 02:05.849
smattering of foreign undergraduate students. 
They mostly take their undergraduate degrees at

02:05.869 --> 02:09.516
home. and then come here for graduate work. So most 
of the foreign students have been taking courses

02:13.116 --> 02:19.283
at the graduate level. I believe earlier you were 
telling me something about the reason why there

02:21.846 --> 02:33.540
has been this tremendous increase in interest in 
poultry

02:21.846 --> 02:33.540
production around the world. And maybe you can 
elaborate on that now. something about trying to

02:36.833 --> 02:42.381
get more protein into the diet. Yes. Well, most of 
the so-called developing nations, we have called

02:43.723 --> 02:58.084
them by different names in the last 15 years, but 
the common term now is developing nations. Most of

02:58.684 --> 03:04.613
the developing nations have their protein source 
in the first place they have been inadequate in the

03:04.593 --> 03:24.255
amount of protein they have had available for 
human consumption and then secondly the major

03:04.593 --> 03:24.255
portion of that protein has been from plant 
sources and most plant proteins other than soy

03:24.235 --> 03:39.855
soybean meal or soy, almost all of the plant 
proteins are deficient in lysine, which is one of

03:24.235 --> 03:39.855
the required essential amino acids, required or 
essential amino acids. It cannot be synthesized

03:40.235 --> 03:43.780
by man himself. And another one is methionine, and 
it cannot be synthesized by man, so it has to be

03:43.760 --> 03:55.997
dietarily provided.

03:57.192 --> 04:18.762
So, these two being low in most of the plant 
proteins that these people had available to them

03:57.192 --> 04:18.762
has meant that they have, in some cases, they have 
actually not had taken full advantage, not been

03:57.192 --> 04:18.762
able to take full advantage are the amount of 
protein they had because of the limitations of

04:18.742 --> 04:25.415
these two particular amino acids. See, they 
couldn't take it from the diet. A human being can't

04:27.098 --> 04:34.152
take the diet, the protein from the diet, 
synthesize it into human protein. by any more than

04:34.132 --> 04:45.066
the limiting, the amino acid that is the lowest, 
the acquired amino acid that's the lowest. And so

04:45.667 --> 04:59.464
for that reason, they have had, I figured a few 
years ago when I was in Bangladesh, I figured at

04:45.667 --> 04:59.464
that time that actually they were throwing away 
are actually using for energy 17% of the protein

04:59.444 --> 05:10.097
they consumed because they didn't have enough 
lysine. And so since meat proteins or animal

05:10.117 --> 05:27.358
proteins are quite high, or animal foods are quite 
high in these two particular amino acids, these

05:10.117 --> 05:27.358
developing countries have been anxious to 
improve their dietary balance by introducing

05:27.338 --> 05:40.352
some animal protein into their consumption now 
many of them what animal protein they get is fish

05:40.771 --> 05:43.997
But there's a limit to how much fish is available. 
In some countries that are not close to the sea,

05:44.017 --> 05:53.716
they can't even take advantage of fish as being one 
of their animal proteins. And so as a result of it,

05:54.357 --> 06:03.775
they have looked to methods of producing animal 
protein and introducing it into their diet. Since

06:04.919 --> 06:23.012
poultry is at the present time the most efficient 
of the common domestic animals, it is the most

06:04.919 --> 06:23.012
efficient converter of feed to food protein that 
we have. And so as a result of it, they have looked to

06:24.173 --> 06:46.621
poultry as being a way of supplementing their 
human diet without robbing their feed supplies,

06:24.173 --> 06:46.621
which some of them are capable of being used for 
human food. And so that has created a national,

06:47.162 --> 06:53.370
international interest in poultry. in poultry as 
a supplier of animal protein for improving the

06:54.160 --> 07:06.435
diets of these developing nations. In fact, I was 
contacted about two weeks ago by one of the men who

07:06.475 --> 07:21.012
had been called by the

07:23.118 --> 07:26.662
administrator of Saudi Arabia. And they, as you 
know, the last few years, most of those

07:27.483 --> 07:36.213
Mid-Eastern countries have all the money they 
want. Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Iraq, etc. They have,

07:40.738 --> 07:45.784
because of the increase in oil prices, they have 
all kinds of money. But agriculture-wise, they

07:46.523 --> 07:49.427
are very deficient. But they do have the money to 
buy from outside, if they can get it to buy. But most

07:55.095 --> 08:06.550
of their people, their rulers, they do not want to 
depend upon continuous importation of their

07:55.095 --> 08:06.550
food. They want to develop their own agriculture 
so that... They can be self-sufficient, or at

08:12.713 --> 08:21.588
least more so in the future than they are at the 
present time. And so they were looking into the

08:22.048 --> 08:35.110
possibility of recruiting a team of American 
scientists who could go over there and develop,

08:22.048 --> 08:35.110
establish a poultry industry in the country. and 
set it up so that it could continue to operate after

08:35.090 --> 08:44.024
the scientists had finished their job. And this is 
being done in New Orleans. Last week at the World's

08:48.771 --> 08:59.308
Party Congress, I was contacted by the man who is in 
charge of the agricultural development for Iraq.

09:00.048 --> 09:15.441
and about the possibility of availability for 
coming over for government consulting work in the

09:00.048 --> 09:15.441
attempt to develop a poultry industry for their 
country. I hope it develops. He'll find somebody

09:17.385 --> 09:18.987
to do it. I don't know who it'll be, but he'll find it 
because money is noâ€”he actually spent nine

09:19.047 --> 09:37.952
million dollars for equipment while he was in New 
Orleans in the exhibit area of the World's

09:19.047 --> 09:37.952
Congress last week. Money's not a problem. No, so 
money's not a problem, right. Has the number of

09:42.117 --> 10:03.197
foreign students from developing countries in 
your graduate program had some influence on the

09:42.117 --> 10:03.197
makeup of the coursework and the requirements for 
a degree, let us say? No, I don't believe so,

10:05.675 --> 10:13.086
because we have tended to have a pretty good 
balance. This, of course, is maybe a prejudiced

10:13.106 --> 10:23.481
opinion, but we think we have a very good balance 
both between courses and of the subject matter

10:23.731 --> 10:48.810
within a given course between the basic material, 
which will work anywhere in the world, and applied

10:23.731 --> 10:48.810
material, which can be used for application to the 
specific problems of producing and feeding and

10:23.731 --> 10:48.810
marketing poultry. And as a result, it has not been 
necessary for us to do a great modification. Well,

10:55.298 --> 11:04.590
I think earlier you indicated that

10:55.298 --> 11:04.590
many of the students which you produce are really 
kind of generalists rather than specialists. And

11:04.630 --> 11:17.025
I was wondering if all of your students had been 
from highly developed countries, if you possibly

11:04.630 --> 11:17.025
would have developed more specialists and fewer 
generalists. No, I think because of the trend we

11:18.068 --> 11:23.112
have been going through. See, we have been, in the 
United States, our units of production have been

11:23.172 --> 11:34.582
getting bigger and fewer. And most of the board of 
directors of an integrated operation want one man

11:35.703 --> 11:47.974
who knows whether this special man, the manager of 
the processing plant, is doing a good job or not. He

11:55.155 --> 12:03.870
also wants to know, wants somebody who can tell him 
or check for him whether this man that's running

11:55.155 --> 12:03.870
the feed mill is doing a good job. And so for that 
reason, domestically, the last 15 years, there's

12:04.677 --> 12:20.314
been a much richer demand for these generalists 
and management and production people than there

12:04.677 --> 12:20.314
were before. And now we're at that stage where I 
think we're going to start going back toward more

12:21.315 --> 12:29.824
specialization. And the foreign countries, the 
developing countries particularly, they can't

12:30.125 --> 12:38.245
afford a geneticist, a nutritionist, and a market 
technologist, and a physiologist in every one of

12:38.444 --> 12:52.477
their operations. And so what they're trying to do 
is to get a little shallower training, but get all

12:52.958 --> 13:08.012
of these disciplines, a workable level of all of 
these disciplines in one man, one or two men, you

12:52.958 --> 13:08.012
see. And so for that reason, I think that explains 
why there's been this number of students

13:07.992 --> 13:21.899
in this area, in this generalized area. Okay.

