14:08.225 --> 14:13.230
with other animals since then.

14:16.394 --> 14:23.241
What would you say had been some of the more 
important research that you had done

14:25.499 --> 14:27.041
since 1946?

14:28.964 --> 14:35.033
Well, this gives me an opportunity to brag an awful 
lot. I hope you won't consider it to be too much so,

14:35.374 --> 14:40.301
but it may sound that way. That's what I'm trying to 
lay the foundation for. Please don't The others

14:47.116 --> 14:50.600
have worked along the same lines and so on. And so 
much of the work has been done by graduate students

14:51.220 --> 14:59.149
and by other staff people and so on. And for that 
reason, I will mention only those areas where I

14:59.710 --> 15:12.904
think we have made at least some original 
contribution to the area, that's all. And I

15:12.884 --> 15:36.669
believe that one of these areas has been the 
development of the idea that for laying hens, we

15:12.884 --> 15:36.669
need to do, for optimum performance and for most 
economical cost of that performance, that

15:12.884 --> 15:36.669
so-called phase feeding is essential. Now, we've 
always phase fed broilers. In other words, we

15:39.952 --> 15:46.482
sometimes have a pre-starter, then a starter, and 
then a finisher diet. But at least if we don't have a

15:46.502 --> 15:50.568
pre-starter, we have a starter and a finisher. Now 
that's only eight weeks. We market our broilers

15:51.830 --> 15:55.916
usually at eight weeks, plus or minus a few days. 
And so this has been accepted. But the tendency up

16:00.182 --> 16:08.575
until a few years ago, the tendency was to 
establish one ration for laying hens and feed this

16:08.555 --> 16:15.004
same ration until the hens had finished their 
production period and were discarded. Actually,

16:16.085 --> 16:35.811
in the winter months we need more energy to keep 
their body temperature up and in the summertime we

16:16.085 --> 16:35.811
need to reduce the energy because the body 
temperature is The environmental temperature,

16:36.854 --> 16:41.620
they lose no heat to the environment, you see. So 
that's what I mean by this phase feeding, just one

16:42.120 --> 16:46.465
element. There's many elements of it. But we need 
to change the ratio of protein to energy, for

16:49.509 --> 16:56.777
example, according to the season. Wintertime, we 
have more energy, less protein. In the summer,

17:01.002 --> 17:05.427
we'll have the same daily consumption. But the 
ratio is what I'm talking about here. Protein,

17:08.752 --> 17:11.115
perhaps, is needed in both seasons. But the ratio 
of energy to protein is higher in the wintertime

17:11.736 --> 17:17.364
and lower in the summer. And the same thing is true 
of calcium, the feed consumption. Our data, we fed

17:24.133 --> 17:32.545
birds individually, and we find that in the 
summertime they may eat only 90 to 95 grams of feed.

17:32.525 --> 17:38.542
Whereas in the wintertime, the feed consumption, 
the same diet, may go up to 115, 120 grams. Well now,

17:38.602 --> 17:47.547
if you're only going to get 90 grams, and the bird's 
laying at the same rate and she's consuming 115

17:38.602 --> 17:47.547
grams, naturally there's got to be some changes 
not just in energy and protein but there's also got

17:47.527 --> 18:04.287
to be some changes in calcium because they've got 
to lay down shells around those eggs and there's

17:47.527 --> 18:04.287
got to be a change in vitamin level because you've 
got to get enough vitamin out of 90 grams And over

18:04.267 --> 18:12.804
here, if you put enough in 90 grams and you put the 
same level in 115 grams, you're wasting a lot of it

18:04.267 --> 18:12.804
down there. So in order for economy, we've simply 
got to go to this so-called phase feeding. Now,

18:20.365 --> 18:31.393
another area where we entered about five years 
ago, we find that we can do more economical feeding

18:20.365 --> 18:31.393
if we control the feed intake. That birds will 
tend, laying birds will tend to overconsume,

18:31.414 --> 18:37.429
consume more than they need to. And gain a little 
extra body weight. Well, the more body weight they

18:39.492 --> 18:44.280
gain, the more the maintenance requirement to 
maintain that body, see? So if we can keep their

18:44.620 --> 18:53.474
body weight down a little bit, we actually make 
more, the cost of feed makes up about two-thirds of

18:44.620 --> 18:53.474
the total cost of producing eggs. So we can do that. 
We had a paper that was reported in New Orleans at

18:55.357 --> 18:59.704
the World Congress last week. it attracted a lot of 
attention. They took up the time for two papers to

19:03.289 --> 19:07.834
ask questions in this area. There were some other 
papers from other countries in the same area. So we

19:12.220 --> 19:22.212
think perhaps here is another area in which we have 
also made some contribution to this. I hadn't had a

19:23.214 --> 19:25.877
chance to think about...

