Could

19:29.013 --> 19:35.513
you stop the...

19:38.446 --> 20:00.691
Another area in which we have worked fairly 
extensively here, and we should do it because we

19:38.446 --> 20:00.691
produce a tremendous amount of grain sorghum in 
this state, and so we have done a lot of feeding of

19:38.446 --> 20:00.691
grain sorghum to poultry, particularly layers. 
Most of my research program has been with layers.

20:03.674 --> 20:24.535
And so we have fed different varieties, different 
colors, that is yellow versus red, and the bird

20:03.674 --> 20:24.535
resistant, we've tested the bird resistant, the 
so-called bird resistant Milo, whether it

20:03.674 --> 20:24.535
actually reduces performance of layers and so on 
or not. I don't know that you've seen it, but there

20:24.515 --> 20:37.868
was about two or three years ago, there was a book 
published on the production and utilization of

20:24.515 --> 20:37.868
grain sorghums. And Dr. Tanksley at Animal 
Science and I were asked to write a chapter on the

20:37.888 --> 20:51.000
feeding of grain sorghums to swine, to poultry, 
and to swine, or to swine and poultry. And so there

20:51.580 --> 20:54.403
is a... as a result of the published material on 
grain sorghum feeding, there is this, and there

20:54.383 --> 21:05.301
are reprints available on this chapter that we 
have. Now, we tried a few years ago, I'm going to

21:07.925 --> 21:21.167
mention this, although it resulted in no 
practical application, a few years ago, I was very

21:07.925 --> 21:21.167
much interested in... how we could improve the 
survival of the poultry embryo from day old, from

21:22.244 --> 21:35.646
the time of setting of the egg, to 21 days when they 
hatch. And so we developed a plastic shell. It's in

21:42.849 --> 21:50.397
two pieces, and it's clear and has a snap on cover. 
And so we got a mold made and had these made for us by

21:51.018 --> 21:59.507
one of the companies in Fort Worth, plastic 
companies. And we tried to use this, we put the

21:59.487 --> 22:13.804
shell, take the egg out of the shell and put it into 
this plastic shell and then put it in the incubator

21:59.487 --> 22:13.804
to try to make it develop. Well, we just don't know, 
and I suspected this might be the case, but we just

22:13.824 --> 22:26.659
don't know enough biology at the present time to 
take that all the way through to 21 days. This is

22:27.921 --> 22:32.368
what I'd like to do, would be to take it all the way 
through to 21 days. Then we could check it for

22:32.729 --> 22:43.045
injections, the effects of different additives, 
feed additives, whether they were toxic or

22:32.729 --> 22:43.045
non-toxic, etc. Just many, many uses could be made 
of this. About all the value it was, or is at this

22:47.092 --> 23:03.666
time to us, or proved to be, we've discontinued any 
interest in it right this minute, but the

22:47.092 --> 23:03.666
youngsters all over the country used this plastic 
eggshell. as a science project in their

23:03.646 --> 23:10.382
school work. And they put these embryos in there 
and they can watch the blood island form on the

23:10.402 --> 23:18.702
germinal disc Then they can watch the blood 
vessels form. Then they can watch the heart form,

23:22.186 --> 23:27.111
and they can see the heart beating and pumping. 
They see it's completely clear, and they can watch

23:27.472 --> 23:36.742
the heart pumping the blood out the arteries and 
back through the veins and so on. So it's been used.

23:38.264 --> 23:43.930
I've shipped those things all over the world, as a 
matter of fact, but particularly over the United

23:38.264 --> 23:43.930
States. I had one extension told him in Ohio that 
